06989nam a22009495i 9783110745511DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021938646  a97831107455117 a10.1515/97831107455112doi  a(DE-B1597)579465  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aBUS0710002bisacsh04aThe Resilient Enterprise :bThriving amid Uncertainty /ced. by Martin Reeves, François Candelon. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (XIII, 119 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInspiring the Next Game00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbout the BCG Henderson Institute -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Building Resilience -- tChapter 1 Resilience vs. Efficiency: Calibrating the Trade-off -- tChapter 2 When Resilience is More Important than Efficiency -- tChapter 3 Advantage in Adversity -- tChapter 4 Die Another Day: What Leaders Can Do About the Shrinking Life Expectancy of Corporations -- tPart II: Developing Ambidexterity -- tChapter 5 Tomorrow Never Dies: The Art of Staying on Top -- tChapter 6 How Vital Companies Think, Act, and Thrive -- tChapter 7 The 2% Company -- tChapter 8 Ambidexterity: The Art of Thriving in Complex Environments -- tPart III: Reinventing Businesses -- tChapter 9 Business Model Innovation -- tChapter 10 Lessons from Mavericks: Staying Big by Acting Small -- tChapter 11 Leaping Before the Platform Burns: The Increasing Necessity of Preemptive Innovation -- tChapter 12 Postmerger Integration Rejuvenation -- tChapter 13 Walking the Tightrope: Successfully Integrating while Transforming -- tList of Figures -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Covid-19 crisis caused massive disruptions to businesses around the world. Many were caught unprepared by the pandemic, putting some in danger of collapse. But not all were equally affected—some emerged from the crisis in a position of advantage. Research on corporate performance over decades shows that the dispersion between companies consistently increases in times of crisis. In other words, resilience to unexpected shocks has a disproportionate impact on long-term competitive advantage. Furthermore, ongoing trends are making it harder for businesses to sustain success over time. New offerings are being adopted, matched, and made obsolete faster, and competitive advantage is becoming less durable. In order to survive in the long run, businesses must reinvent themselves regularly—doing the same thing over and over will eventually lead to failure. Many business leaders are now expressing an intention to make their companies more resilient, but there is not yet a well-codified playbook for doing so. This book, drawing on research from the BCG Henderson Institute over many years, provides a set of perspectives on how to thrive under adverse conditions and how to reinvent businesses for the changing context. Overcoming both of these challenges is necessary for leaders to build long-lasting companies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Leadership.2bisacsh1 aBarrett, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergman, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBham, Salman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCandelon, François, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCharme di Carlo, Rodolphe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeimler, Michael S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDesai, Sasi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaanæs, Knut, ec